Fran\u231?ois-Marie Arouet (1694\u8211?1778), who later took the name of Voltaire, was the son of a notary, and educated at a Jesuit school in Paris. Although his father wished him to study law, he determined on a literary career. Gaining an introduction to the intellectual life of Paris, he soon won a not altogether enviable reputation as a writer of satires and odes, for the suspicion of having written a satire on the Regent resulted in six months\u8217? imprisonment in the Bastille. On his release, his first tragedy, {\i
Oedipe}, was performed (1718) in Paris with great success; and soon after he published a national epic poem he had written in prison, {\i
La Henriade} (1724), which placed him with Homer and Virgil in the eyes of his contemporaries. After a second term of imprisonment in the Bastille, Voltaire spent the years 1726\u8211?9 in England, and returned to France full of enthusiasm for the intellectual activity and the more tolerant form of government he had found there. His enthusiasm and his indictment of the French system of government are expressed in his {\i
Philosophic Letters} (1733), whose sale was forbidden in France. The next fifteen years were spent at the country seat of his friend, Madame du Ch\u226?telet, where he wrote his most popular tragedies and {\i
Zadig}, a witty Eastern tale, and started work on his {\i
Century of Louis XIV}. After Madame du Ch\u226?telet\u8217?s death in 1749, Voltaire visited the court of Frederick the Great, and while there completed his historical work, {\i
Essay on Customs (Essai sur les Moeurs et l\u8217?Esprit des Nations)}, and began his {\i
Philosophic Dictionary}, but he and Frederick did not agree for long, and in 1753 he left Prussia. France was still unsafe, and after two years\u8217? wandering he settled in Geneva. During his last, most brilliant, twenty years, he wrote {\i
Candide}, his dialogues, and more tales, and published his {\i
Philosophical Dictionary} (1764) in \u8216?pocket\u8217? form, while conducting a ceaseless attack on what he called the \u8216?infamous thing\u8217?, i.e. all manifestations of tyranny and persecution by a privileged orthodoxy in Church and State. He died aged eighty-four after a triumphant visit to Paris from which he had been exiled for so long.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
