BIOGRAPHICAL NOTE\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
FRAN\u199?OISE-MARIE AROUET (1694\u8211?1778), who later took the name of Voltaire, was the son of a notary and educated at a Jesuit school in Paris. His father wanted him to study the law, but the young man was determined on a literary career. He gained an introduction to the intellectual life of Paris, and soon won a reputation as a writer of satires and odes \u8211? a not altogether enviable reputation, for the suspicion of having written a satire on the Regent procured him a term of six months\u8217? imprisonment in the Bastille. On his release, his first tragedy, {\i
\u338?dipe}, was performed (1718) in Paris with great success; and soon after he published the poem he had written in prison, a national epic, {\i
La Henriade} (1724), which placed him with Homer and Virgil in the eyes of his contemporaries.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
After a second term of imprisonment in the Bastille, Voltaire spent three years (1726\u8211?9) in England, and returned to France full of enthusiasm for the intellectual activity and the more tolerant form of government he found in this country. His enthusiasm and his indictment of the French system of government are expressed in his {\i
Philosophic Letters} (1733), whose sale was absolutely forbidden in France.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
The next fifteen years were spent at the country seat of his friend, Madame du Ch\u226?telet, where he wrote {\i
Zadig} and his most popular tragedies, and started work on his {\i
Century of Louis XIV}.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
After Mme du Ch\u226?telet\u8217?s death in 1749, Voltaire was induced to pay a prolonged visit to the Court of Frederick the Great, with whom he had been in correspondence for several years. While there he completed his important historical work {\i
Essay on Customs (Essai sur les m\u339?urs et l\u8217?esprit des nations)}, and began his {\i
Philosophic Dictionary}. Voltaire and Frederick could not agree for long, and in 1753 Voltaire decided to leave Prussia. But he was not safe in France. After two years of wandering, he settled near Geneva, and at last made a home at Ferney.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
It was during these last, and most brilliant, twenty years of his life that he wrote {\i
Candide}, his dialogues, and more tales, including {\i
L\u8217?Ing\u233?nu}, and published his widely-read {\i
Philosophic Dictionary} (1764) in \u8216?pocket\u8217? form while conducting his ceaseless and energetic attack against what he called the \u8216?infamous thing\u8217? \u8211? that is to say, all manifestations of tyranny and persecution by a privileged orthodoxy in church and state.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
He died at the age of eighty-four, after a triumphant visit to the Paris from which he had been exiled for so long.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{\par\pard\hyphpar }{\page } {\s1 \afs32
