THE DOG AND THE HORSE\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
ZADIG found, as it is written in the Book of Zend, that the first month of marriage is the Honeymoon and the second is the Wormwoodmoon. It was not long before he was obliged to divorce Azora, who had become too difficult to live with, and he decided to seek consolation in the study of Nature.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?There is no greater happiness,\u8217? said he, \u8216?than that which a philosopher enjoys in reading the great book which God has set before our eyes. The truths he there discovers become his own. He feasts his spirit with lofty thoughts. He lives a life of tranquillity, in which no man gives him cause for fear and and no loving wife comes to cut off his nose.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
Full of these ideas, he retired to a country seat on the banks of the Euphrates. He did not spend his time there in calculating how many inches of water flowed each second under the arches of a bridge, or whether the signs of the Zodiac affect the rainfall: whether the month of the mouse, for instance, is wetter than the month of the sheep. He did not speculate on how to make silk from spiders\u8217? webs, or china from broken bottles; but he did study the properties of animals and plants, and soon learned to recognize subtle differences which others failed to discern.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
One day as he was walking near a little wood he saw one of the Queen\u8217?s eunuchs running towards him, followed by several Officers of the Guard who seemed to be in great anxiety. They were rushing hither and thither like men distracted, looking for some precious object which they had lost.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Young man,\u8217? said the chief eunuch to Zadig, \u8216?have you seen the Queen\u8217?s dog anywhere?\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?It is a bitch, not a dog,\u8217? replied Zadig, modestly.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Yes, you\u8217?re right,\u8217? said the chief eunuch.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?It is a little Spaniel bitch,\u8217? Zadig went on. \u8216?She has recently had puppies, she limps in the left foreleg, and her ears are very long.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Then you have seen her,\u8217? said the chief eunuch, quite out of breath.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?No,\u8217? replied Zadig. \u8216?I have never seen her. I never even knew that the Queen had a bitch.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
At that very moment, by one of the customary freaks of fortune, the finest horse in the King\u8217?s stable had escaped from the hands of its groom on the plains of Babylon. The chief huntsman and all the remaining officers were running after it in as much anxiety as the chief eunuch had shown for the bitch. The chief huntsman went up to Zadig and asked him if he had seen the King\u8217?s horse go by.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?There isn\u8217?t a better galloper,\u8217? replied Zadig. \u8216?It is five foot high, with remarkably small hooves, and a tail three and a half feet long. The bosses on its bit are of twenty-three carat gold, and it is shod with silver of eleven deniers proof.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Which way did it go? Where is it?\u8217? asked the chief huntsman.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?I have not seen it,\u8217? replied Zadig. \u8216?This is the first I\u8217?ve heard of it.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
The chief huntsman and the chief eunuch were in no doubt that Zadig had stolen the King\u8217?s horse and the Queen\u8217?s bitch. They had him brought before the Lord Treasurer\u8217?s court, who sentenced him to be flogged and to spend the rest of his days in Siberia. The sentence was scarcely passed when the horse and the bitch were found. The judges were therefore in the painful position of having to alter their decision; but they sentenced Zadig to pay four hundred ounces of gold for having declared that he had not seen what he had seen. The fine had first to be paid, but Zadig was afterwards allowed to plead his cause before the Lord Treasurer\u8217?s Council. He spoke as follows:\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Luminaries of Justice! Unfathomable Depths of Knowledge! Mirrors of Truth, who possess the weight of lead, the strength of iron, the brilliance of diamonds, and a close resemblance to gold! Being granted permission to speak before this august assembly, I swear to you by Ormuzd that I have never seen the Queen\u8217?s most honourable bitch nor the sacred horse belonging to the King of Kings. This is what happened. I was taking a walk near the coppice where I afterwards met the most reverend eunuch and the most illustrious chief huntsman. I noticed the tracks of an animal in the sandy soil, which I readily took to be those of a little dog. Some long but delicate furrows, traced in the sand wherever it was raised between the prints of the paws, showed me that it was a bitch with hanging dugs, which must therefore have had puppies a few days before. Other tracks of a different kind, which always appeared to have brushed the sand at either side of the forefeet, showed me that its ears were very long; and as I noticed that the sand was always more deeply impressed by one paw than by the other three, I concluded that our august Queen\u8217?s little bitch was a trifle lame, if I may dare to say so.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?As for the horse which belongs to the King of Kings, you must know that as I was walking along the paths of this wood, I noticed some horseshoe prints all at equal distances. \u8220?There\u8217?s a horse with a fine gallop,\u8221? I said to myself. In a straight stretch of path only seven feet wide, the dust had been lightly brushed from the trees on both sides at a distance of three and a half feet from the centre of the path. \u8220?This horse,\u8221? said I, \u8220?has a tail three and a half feet long, which must have swept off the dust on both sides as it waved.\u8221? The trees formed an arcade five feet high. When I noticed that some of the leaves were newly fallen, I deduced that the horse must have touched them, and that he was therefore five feet high also. As for the bit, it must be made of twenty-three carat gold, because the horse had rubbed the bosses against a stone which I knew to be touchstone, and which I therefore tested. And finally I judged from the marks which the horseshoes had left on a different kind of stone that it was shod with silver of eleven deniers proof.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
The assembled judges admired Zadig\u8217?s deep and subtle penetration. The news of it even reached the King and Queen. In the antechambers, in the drawing room, and in the council chamber no one talked of anything but Zadig; and though several mages considered that he should be burnt as a sorcerer, the King commanded the fine of four hundred ounces of gold to which he had been sentenced to be repaid to him. The Clerk of the Court, the Gentlemen Ushers, and the Procurators Fiscal visited him in great state to repay the four hundred ounces. They retained a mere three hundred and ninety-eight of them for legal expenses, and their servants had to be tipped.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
Zadig saw how dangerous it sometimes is to be too clever, and he determined on the next occasion to say nothing of what he had seen.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
The occasion soon arrived. A prisoner of state escaped, and passed by Zadig\u8217?s window. Zadig was questioned and made no reply. But he was proved to have been looking out of his window, and was condemned for this crime to pay five hundred ounces of gold. He thanked the judges for their clemency, as the custom is in Babylon.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Good Heavens,\u8217? he said to himself. \u8216?What trouble a man can get into if he takes a walk in a wood after the Queen\u8217?s bitch and the King\u8217?s horse have passed by! How dangerous it is to sit at a window, and how difficult to be happy in this life!\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{\par\pard\hyphpar }{\page } {\s1 \afs32
