THE BEATEN WOMAN\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
ZADIG took his course by the stars. The constellation of Orion and the brilliance of Sirius directed his steps towards Canopus. He was lost in admiration for these vast spheres of light, which look to our eyes like feeble sparks only because the Earth, which is in reality a mere imperceptible point in the Universe, appears to our greedy outlook something noble and grand. Then he pictured to himself men as they really are, insects devouring one another on a tiny fragment of mud. The truth of this conception seemed to annihilate his misfortunes as he recalled to mind the utter nothingness of his own being and of Babylon too. His spirit soared into space; and with the grossness of the senses left behind, he meditated upon the unchangeable laws of the heavenly universe. But when he returned to himself a moment later, and looked into his heart, and thought that Astarte had perhaps perished for his sake, the Universe disappeared from his view, and all he saw in the whole range of Nature was Astarte dying and his ill-fated self.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
While surrendering himself alternately to sublime philosophy and overwhelming grief, he drew near to the frontiers of Egypt; his faithful servant had already reached the first settlement, and was looking for lodgings there. Meanwhile Zadig took a walk towards the gardens at the edge of the village. Not far from the road he saw a woman in tears, crying aloud to Heaven and Earth for help, and pursued by a man in a violent temper. She had just been overtaken by the man, and had thrown herself at his feet, with her arms round his knees; but the fellow loaded her with blows and re proaches. Judging by the Egyptian\u8217?s violence and by the lady\u8217?s repeated appeals for pardon, Zadig took the one to be jealous and the other unfaithful; but when he regarded the lady, who was strikingly beautiful and even bore some resemblance to the unfortunate Astarte, he felt moved by compassion for her, and was horrified at the Egyptian.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Help me,\u8217? she cried to Zadig amidst her sobs. \u8216?Deliver me from the hands of the most barbarous of men, and save my life!\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
At this appeal he ran and threw himself between her and the cruel wretch. He had some knowledge of the Egyptian tongue; and addressing him in that language, he said:\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?If you have any humanity, I conjure you to be merciful to weakness and beauty. How could you treat this masterpiece of nature so cruelly! She is at your feet, and she has no defence but her tears!\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Oho!\u8217? said the fellow, in a transport of rage. \u8216?So you are sweet upon her too! I\u8217?ll have my revenge on you, then.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
With those words; he let go the lady, whom he was holding by the hair, and tried to stab the stranger with his lance. Zadig, whose temper was cool, had no difficulty in avoiding an angry man\u8217?s attack, and seized the lance by its iron tip. While the one tried to snatch it away and the other tried to get possession of it, the lance broke in their hands. At that, the Egyptian drew his sword; Zadig did likewise, and they fell upon each other. The former dealt a hundred violent blows, which the latter skilfully parried. Meanwhile the lady sat down on the grass, tidied her hair, and watched them. The Egyptian was more robust than his adversary, but Zadig was more adroit. He fought skilfully, his brain guiding his arm, while the other fought like a maniac whose blind rage directs his movements at random. Zadig made a pass at him, and disarmed him. This made the Egyptian more furious; but while trying to fling himself upon his opponent, he was seized by Zadig, who pressed home the attack and brought him to the ground. Then, with a sword at the Egyptian\u8217?s breast, Zadig offered him his life. The Egyptian was beside himself with rage; drawing his dagger, he wounded Zadig with it at the moment when his victor was offering him mercy. Roused to indignation, Zadig plunged his sword into the man\u8217?s breast, and the Egyptian, uttering a horrible cry, fell back and died. Zadig then approached the lady, and gently said to her:\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?He forced me to kill him. I have avenged you, and you are delivered from the most violent man I ever saw. What would you have of me now, madam?\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Your death, you villain!\u8217? she replied, \u8216?your death! You have slain my lover. I could tear your heart out!\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Indeed, madam,\u8217? replied Zadig, \u8216?that\u8217?s a strange man to have for a lover. He was beating you as hard as he could, and he wanted to take my life because you begged me to come to your help.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?I wish he were still alive to beat me,\u8217? cried the lady. \u8216?I deserved it, for I had given him cause to be jealous. Would to God he were beating me, and you were in his place!\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
Zadig was more surprised and angry than he had ever been in his life. \u8216?Madam,\u8217? said he, \u8216?beautiful as you are, it would serve you right if I were to beat you now myself, since you talk so absurdly. But I shall not give myself the trouble.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
Thereupon he remounted his camel and set off for the town. He had not gone far before he turned round on hearing the noise of four horsemen, couriers from Babylon, who were riding at full speed. One of them noticed the woman, and cried, \u8216?That\u8217?s her. She is just like the description we\u8217?ve been given.\u8217? They took no heed of the dead man, and unceremoniously laid hold of the lady, whereupon she kept calling to Zadig: \u8216?Help me once more, generous stranger! Forgive me for reproaching you. Help me, and I am yours till death.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
But Zadig\u8217?s desire to fight for her was now gratified. \u8216?It\u8217?s other people\u8217?s turn,\u8217? he replied. \u8216?You won\u8217?t catch me again.\u8217? Besides, he was wounded and bleeding. and had need of attention; and the sight of four Babylonians, probably sent by King Moabdar, filled him with disquiet. He hastened towards the village, unable to conceive why four couriers from Babylon should come and arrest this Egyptian woman, and rapt in astonishment at the character of the lady herself.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{\par\pard\hyphpar }{\page } {\s1 \afs32
