THE FUNERAL PYRE\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
SETOC was delighted, and made an intimate friend of his slave. Like the King of Babylon, he could no longer do without him; and Zadig was glad that Setoc had no wife. He discovered that his master was naturally benevolent, and possessed a large measure of honesty and good sense; but he was displeased to see him worshipping the celestial host, that is to say the Sun, the Moon, and the Stars, as the ancient custom is in Arabia. He spoke to him about it with great discretion on several occasions. At length he told him that these bodies were in no way supernatural, and deserved no more homage than a rock or a tree.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?But,\u8217? said Setoc, \u8216?they are eternal beings from which we derive all benefits: they give life to Nature, they rule the seasons, and they are besides so far-removed from us that one can\u8217?t help revering them.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?You derive more good,\u8217? replied Zadig, \u8216?from the waters of the Red Sea which bears your merchandise to the Indies. Why shouldn\u8217?t that be as old as the stars? And if you worship what is so remote, you ought to worship the land of the Gangarides, which is at the other end of the world.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?No,\u8217? said Setoc. \u8216?The stars are so brilliant that I cannot help worshipping them.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
That same evening Zadig lit a great number of candles in the tent where he was to have supper with Setoc, and as soon as his patron arrived, he fell upon his knees before the lighted tapers, and addressed them thus :\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Bright and everlasting luminaries, look ever favourably upon me.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
Having uttered these words, he sat down to table without taking any notice of Setoc.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?What on earth are you doing?\u8217? said Setoc to him in astonishment.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?I am doing what you do,\u8217? replied Zadig. \u8216?I am worshipping these candles, and I am taking no notice of their master and mine.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
Setoc perceived the meaning underlying this performance. His slave\u8217?s wisdom entered into his soul, and instead of wasting incense on the objects of Creation, he worshipped the Eternal Being who made them.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
There was at that time in Arabia a horrible custom which originally came from Scythia; it had been established in India by the authority of the Brahmins, and threatened to overrun the whole of the East. When a married man died and his devoted wife wished to be assured of sanctification, she burnt herself alive in public on the body of her husband. It was a solemn festival, and was called the Pyre of Widowhood. The tribe which could claim the greatest number of burned women was the most respected. An Arab of Setoc\u8217?s tribe had died; and his widow, Almona, a very devout woman, had announced the day and hour when she would throw herself into the fire to the sound of tambours and trumpets. Zadig represented to Setoc that this horrible custom was contrary to the welfare of the human race; he pointed out that every day young widows were allowed to be burned who could have produced children for the State, or who could at least have brought up their own; and he made him agree that if possible such a barbarous custom should be abolished. But Setoc replied:\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?For more than a thousand years women have had the right to burn themselves. Which of us shall dare to alter a law which time has consecrated? Is there anything more respectable than an ancient abuse?\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Reason is more ancient,\u8217? replied Zadig. \u8216?Speak to the leaders of the tribes, while I go and find the young widow.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
He gained admission to her, and after ingratiating himself with praise of her beauty, and saying what a pity it was that so many charms should be committed to the flames, he praised her still more for her constancy and courage.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?You must have been devoted to your husband,\u8217? he said to her.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Indeed I wasn\u8217?t,\u8217? replied the Arabian lady. \u8216?He was a brutal creature, consumed with jealousy, a quite insufferable fellow; but I am firmly resolved to throw myself upon his funeral pyre.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?There must evidently be a most delicious pleasure in being burnt alive,\u8217? said Zadig.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Ah,\u8217? said the lady, \u8216?it makes me tremble to think of it, but it has to be endured. I am a devout woman, and I should lose my reputation. Everyone would laugh at me if I did not burn myself.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
After making her agree that she was going to burn herself in deference to others and to gratify her vanity, Zadig spoke to her at length in such a way as to make her feel some love of living. He even succeeded in arousing in her a measure of goodwill towards himself.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Well, then, what will you do,\u8217? he said, \u8216?if you decide not to make this useless sacrifice?\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
The lady sighed, as she answered: \u8216?I think I should beg you to marry me.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
This declaration made no appeal to Zadig, whose mind was still possessed by the image of Astarte; but he went immediately to find the leaders of the tribes and tell them what had happened. He advised them to make a law forbidding a widow to burn herself until after she had conversed in private with a young man for the space of a whole hour. Since that time not a woman in Arabia has burnt herself alive. To Zadig alone was the credit due of having destroyed in one day such a cruel custom, which had lasted for so many centuries. He was therefore the benefactor of Arabia.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{\par\pard\hyphpar }{\page } {\s1 \afs32
