THE CHILD OF NATURE IS RECOGNIZED BY HIS RELATIVES\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
THE Child of Nature awoke as usual at daybreak with the crowing of the cock, \u8216?the trumpet of day\u8217? as they call it in England and in Huronia. He was not like people in high-society who linger idly in their beds till the sun has run half his course, unable either to sleep or to get up, and who lose so many precious hours in that state halfway between life and death, yet are always complaining that life is too short.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
He had covered five or six miles and finished off thirty head of game in as many shots, before coming back to find the Prior of Our Lady of the Mountain and his modest sister in their nightcaps taking a walk in their little garden. He laid at their feet all the game he had dispatched, and then begged them to accept, in recognition of their kind reception, a sort of little talisman which he always wore round his neck and which he now produced from under his shirt.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?It\u8217?s the most precious thing I possess,\u8217? he told them. \u8216?I have been assured that I should always be happy so long as I wear this little trinket, and now I give it you to secure your happiness.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
The Prior and the lady smiled tenderly at the Child of Nature\u8217?s simplicity. The present consisted of two crudely painted miniatures held together by a greasy strap.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
Mademoiselle de Kerkabon asked him whether they had painters in Huronia.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?No,\u8217? replied the Child of Nature. \u8216?This rarity came to me from my nurse. All that I know of it is that her husband acquired it as spoils of war from some French Canadians.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
The Prior looked closely at the portraits. His colour changed, and he became so agitated that his hands trembled.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?By Our Lady of the Mountain,\u8217? he exclaimed. \u8216?That\u8217?s the face of my brother the Captain, I feel sure, and that\u8217?s his wife\u8217?s!\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
Mademoiselle de Kerkabon examined them with the same excitement, and came to the same conclusion. Both were rapt with astonishment. The joy they felt was mingled with grief, and tears of tenderness welled in their eyes. Their hearts throbbed, and they uttered cries as they snatched the portraits from each other, exchanging them at least twenty times a second.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
They eagerly compared the portraits with the Huron\u8217?s features, and implored him one after another, and both at the same time, to tell them when, where, and how these miniatures had fallen into the hands of his nurse. They agreed in their reckoning of the time that had elapsed since the Captain\u8217?s departure; they remembered receiving news that he had reached the land of the Hurons, and that after that they had heard no more of him.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
The Child of Nature had told them that he had known neither father nor mother. The Prior, who was an intelligent man, noticed that the Child of Nature had a small beard, and he knew very well that Hurons are beardless.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?His chin is downy, so he must be the son of a European. My brother and my sister-in-law never reappeared after the expedition against the Hurons in 1699. My nephew must still have been at the breast. His Huron nurse saved his life and was a mother to him.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
At last, after innumerable questions and answers, the Prior and his sister decided that the Huron really was their own nephew. They embraced him with tears in their eyes, and the young man laughed at the idea of a Huron being the nephew of a Breton Prior.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
At this point the other guests appeared. Monsieur de St Yves, who was a great physiognomist, compared both portraits with the Huron\u8217?s face, and very cleverly pointed out that he had his mother\u8217?s eyes, the late Captain Kerkabon\u8217?s forehead and nose, and cheeks which belonged to both of them.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
Mademoiselle de St Yves, who had never seen either the mother or the father, was in no doubt that the resemblance was perfect. They were astonished at the ways of Providence, and at the chain of events in this world. At last, such was their persuasion, nay conviction, about his birth, that the Child of Nature himself consented to be the nephew of the Prior, saying that he would make as good an uncle as anyone else.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
While thanks were given to God in the Church of Our Lady of the Mountain, the Huron, with an air of indifference, stayed in the house drinking until the English who had brought him came to tell him that they were ready to set sail and it was time to leave.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Apparently,\u8217? said he, \u8216?you have not been reunited with your uncles and aunts. I am staying here. Go back to Plymouth and you can have all my clothes, for I have no more need of anything as I am the nephew of a Prior.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
The English set sail, not caring overmuch whether the Huron had found relatives in Lower Brittany or not.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
After uncle, aunt, and the whole company had sung the Te Deum, and the Magistrate had once more overwhelmed the Huron with questions, and they had exhausted everything that astonishment, joy, and tenderness could bring to mind, the Prior of the Mountain and the Abb\u233? de St Yves decided that they must baptize the young man without further delay. But it was not the same thing christening a great Huron twenty-two years old as regenerating a baby who knows nothing of what is going on. He must be instructed, and that seemed to raise a difficulty, because the Abb\u233? de St Yves did not imagine that a man not born in France could have any common sense.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
The Prior, on the other hand, reminded the company that although his nephew had not had the good fortune to be born in Lower Brittany, he had intelligence none the less, as they could judge from his replies; and surely he had been greatly blessed by nature in both his parents.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
The first question was, had he read any books? He said he had read an English translation of Rabelais, and some extracts from Shakespeare, which he knew by heart; these were books which he had found in the cabin of the vessel which brought him from America to Plymouth, and they had given him great pleasure. The Magistrate seized the opportunity to question him about these books.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?I admit,\u8217? said the Huron, \u8216?that I thought I understood something, and didn\u8217?t fathom the rest.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
The Abb\u233? de St Yves reflected that this had always been his own way of reading, and that of most other people.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?You have read the Bible, of course?\u8217? he asked the Huron.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Never, Monsieur l\u8217?Abb\u233?,\u8217? was the reply. \u8216?It was not among the Captain\u8217?s books. I have never heard of it.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Just like those accursed English!\u8217? cried Mademoiselle de Kerkabon. \u8216?A play by Shakespeare, a plum pudding, a bottle of rum, mean more to them than the Pentateuch! And so, they have never converted anybody in America. There\u8217?s no doubt about it, they are cursed by God; we shall take Jamaica and Virginia from them in no time!\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
Be that as it may, the most skilful tailor in St Malo was sent for to clothe the Child of Nature from head to foot. The party broke up; the Magistrate went off to ask his questions elsewhere. Mademoiselle de St Yves could not tear herself away and kept turning round to look at the Child of Nature, who bowed to her more deeply than he had ever done to anyone in his life.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
Before the Magistrate said farewell, he introduced Mademoiselle de St Yves to his great booby of a son just fresh from school; but she hardly noticed him, so preoccupied was she with the politeness of the Huron.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{\par\pard\hyphpar }{\page } {\s1 \afs32
