THE CHILD OF NATURE IN LOVE\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
IT must be admitted that from the time of this baptism and dinner Mademoiselle de St Yves felt a passionate longing for the Bishop to make her a participant in some other beautiful sacrament with Monsieur Hercules, the Child of Nature. She was too well brought up and too modest, however, to give these tender sentiments full rein even to herself; but if a look, a word, a gesture, or a thought escaped her, she concealed it in a veil of modesty that was infinitely charming. She was tender and lively, and she was wise.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
As soon as the Bishop had departed, the Child of Nature and Mademoiselle de St Yves found themselves together without noticing that the one had sought the other\u8217?s company. They talked to each other without having thought what they would say. The Child of Nature told her immediately that he loved her with all his heart, and that the beautiful Abacaba, whom he had worshipped in his own country, was not to be compared to her. The lady replied, with her usual modesty, that he must speak straight away to his uncle the Prior, and to his aunt; she for her part would drop a word into her dear brother\u8217?s ear, and she was confident that they would all give their consent.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
The Huron replied that there was no need for anyone\u8217?s consent, and that he thought it was quite ridiculous to go and ask others what to do; for when two parties were agreed, there was no need of a third to bring them together.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?I don\u8217?t consult anyone,\u8217? he said, \u8216?when I want to have breakfast, or to go hunting, or to go to sleep, though I quite understand that in love it\u8217?s not a bad idea to have the consent of the person concerned. But as I am not in love with my uncle or my aunt, I have no need to consult them over this; and if you take my advice, you\u8217?ll leave the Abb\u233? de St Yves out of it as well.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
Of course the lovely Breton used all her tact to reduce her Huron to a state of decorum. She even became angry, but she soon relented. There is no knowing how the conversation would have ended if the Abb\u233? had not appeared at sunset to take his sister home. The Child of Nature let his uncle and aunt retire to bed, for they were a little tired after the ceremony and their lengthy dinner. He spent part of the night composing verses to his beloved in the Huron language, for one must remember that love will make lovers into poets the whole world over.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
Next morning his uncle spoke to him after breakfast, in the presence of Mademoiselle de Kerkabon, who was much moved by the scene :\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Heaven be praised, my dear nephew, that you have the honour of being a Christian and a Low Breton! But this is not enough. I am getting on in years. My brother left only a small plot of ground worth very little; but I have a fine Priory. If you will only be ordained a sub-deacon, as I hope you will, I will resign my Priory to you, and you will live very comfortably, after being the consolation of my old age.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Much good may it do you, my dear uncle,\u8217? replied the Child of Nature. \u8216?You must live as long as you can. I have no idea what it means to be a sub-deacon, nor to resign; but anything will suit me so long as I can have Mademoiselle de St Yves.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Good Heavens, nephew, what are you talking about? Are you really so much in love with that beautiful girl?\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Yes, uncle, indeed I am.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?I am sorry, nephew, but it is quite impossible for you to marry her.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?On the contrary, uncle, it\u8217?s altogether possible. She not only took my hand when she left me, but she promised to be my wife, and I shall certainly marry her.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?I tell you it is out of the question. She is your godmother. It is a deadly sin for a godmother to take her godson\u8217?s hand! A man is forbidden to marry his godmother; the laws of Heaven and earth are against it.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?I believe you must be teasing me, uncle! Why should it be forbidden to marry one\u8217?s godmother when she is young and pretty? I saw nothing in the Book you gave me to say that it was wrong to marry girls who have helped people to be baptized. I notice every day that innumerable things go on here which are not in your Book, and that nobody follows what it says. I own it surprises me, it shocks me. If I am deprived of the lovely St Yves under pretext of my baptism, I warn you I shall carry her off and unbaptize myself.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
The Prior was confounded; and his sister burst into tears.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?My dear brother,\u8217? said she, \u8216?our nephew mustn\u8217?t damn himself. Surely our Holy Father the Pope can give him a dispensation, and then he will be able to live a happy Christian life with his beloved.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
The Child of Nature embraced his aunt.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Tell me, who is this delightful man,\u8217? he asked, \u8216?who is so kind to boys and girls in love? I\u8217?ll go and speak to him straight away.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
They explained to him who the Pope was, and the Child of Nature was even more astonished than before.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?There is not a word of all this in your Book, my dear uncle. I have travelled; I know what the sea is like. Here we are on the shores of the Atlantic. It\u8217?s a ridiculous idea, quite incomprehensible, that I should leave Mademoiselle de St Yves to go and ask permission to love her from a man who lives by the Mediterranean, four hundred leagues from here. Besides, I shouldn\u8217?t understand what he said! I am going straight to the Abb\u233? de St Yves, who lives only a league from here, and I tell you I shall marry my darling this day.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
While he was still talking, the Magistrate entered, and as usual wanted to know where he was going.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?I am going to be married,\u8217? replied the Child of Nature, as he ran off; and a quarter of an hour later he was already at the house of his charming and beloved Breton, who was still asleep.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
Meanwhile Mademoiselle de Kerkabon was remarking to the Prior with a sigh, \u8216?Brother, you\u8217?ll never make our nephew a sub-deacon.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
The Magistrate was very much displeased by this expedition, because he intended his son to marry Mademoiselle de St Yves; and this son was even more stupid and unbearable than his father.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{\par\pard\hyphpar }{\page } {\s1 \afs32
