THE ARRIVAL OF THE CHILD OF NATURE AT VERSAILLES, AND HIS RECEPTION AT COURT\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
THE Child of Nature alighted from his \u8216?chamber-pot\u8217? {\super
*} in the kitchen yard. He asked the chairmen what time the King could be seen. They laughed in his face, just as the English Admiral had done, and he treated them in just the same way; that is to say, he boxed their ears. They began to retaliate, and the scene would have been bloody had not a Breton gentleman who was one of the officers of the guard appeared and dispersed the rabble.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?You seem to me a brave man, sir,\u8217? said the traveller. \u8216?I am the nephew of the Prior of Our Lady of the Mountain. I have killed some Englishmen, and I have come to speak to the King. I beg you to take me to his room.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
The officer was delighted to discover a gallant man from his own province who appeared ignorant of Court customs, and informed him that one did not go straight in and speak to the King, as it was necessary to be presented by Monseigneur de Louvois.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Very well, take me to this Monseigneur de Louvois; no doubt he will conduct me to His Majesty.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?To talk to Monseigneur de Louvois,\u8217? replied the officer, \u8216?is even more difficult than to talk to His Majesty. But I will take you to Monsieur Alexandre, the First Secretary for War. It will be just as good as talking to the Minister.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
Off they went accordingly to see this Monsieur Alexandre, the First Secretary; but they could not be admitted. He was engaged with a lady of the Court, and had given orders that no one was to be allowed in.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Never mind,\u8217? said the officer, \u8216?that\u8217?s no great loss. Let us go to Monsieur Alexandre\u8217?s First Secretary. It will be just as good as talking to Monsieur Alexandre himself.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
The Huron followed him in astonishment, and they waited half an hour in a little antechamber.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?What\u8217?s all this?\u8217? asked the Child of Nature. \u8216?Is everyone invisible in this part of the world? It is much easier to fight the English in Lower Brittany than it is to find the people you have to deal with at Versailles.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
He passed the time by telling his compatriot about his love affairs. But the hour struck and recalled the officer to his post. They promised to meet again the next day, and the Child of Nature waited another half hour in the antechamber, dreaming of Mademoiselle de St Yves and the difficulty of speaking to Kings and First Secretaries.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
At last the chief appeared.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Sir,\u8217? said the Child of Nature, addressing him, \u8216?if I had waited as long to repel the English as you have kept me waiting for audience, they would now be ravaging Lower Brittany at their leisure.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
These words attracted the Secretary\u8217?s attention, and he said to the Breton: \u8216?What do you want?\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?My reward,\u8217? replied the other. \u8216?Here\u8217?s proof of what I\u8217?ve done,\u8217? and he held out all his certificates. The Secretary read them, and told him that he would probably be allowed to buy himself a commission.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?What\u8217?s that you say? I am to put down some money for driving the English off? To pay for the privilege of getting myself killed for you, while you sit here quietly giving audiences? You must be joking. I want a company of cavalry for nothing. I want the King to get Mademoiselle de St Yves out of her convent and give her to me in marriage. I want to plead with the King on behalf of fifty thousand families, whom I mean to restore to him. In short, I want to be useful, I want to be employed and get on in the world.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?What is your name, Sir, that you talk so loudly?\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Oh indeed,\u8217? replied the Child of Nature. \u8216?So you haven\u8217?t read my testimonials? That\u8217?s the treatment you get, is it? My name is Hercules de Kerkabon, I have been baptized, I am lodging at the Blue Dial, and I shall complain of you to the King.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
The Secretary concluded, as the people of Saumur had done, that he was not quite right in the head, and did not take much notice of him.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
The same day, the Reverend Father de La Chaise, confessor to Louis XIV, had received the letter from his spy accusing the Breton Kerkabon of taking sides with the Huguenots and condemning the conduct of the Jesuits. Monseigneur de Louvois, for his part, had received a letter from the inquisitive Magistrate describing the Huron as a young rogue who wanted to set fire to convents and carry off the girls.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
The Child of Nature took a turn in the gardens of Versailles, which did not appeal to him, and dined like a Huron and a Low Breton; he went to bed with the delicious thought of seeing the King next day, obtaining the hand of Mademoiselle de St Yves in marriage, commanding at least a cavalry company, and ending the persecution of the Huguenots. He was indulging himself with these flattering visions when the police entered his room.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
They first seized his double-barrelled gun and his great broadsword. Then they made a record of his ready money, and carried him off to that sinister fortress built by King Charles V, son of John II, near the rue St Antoine at the Tournelles gate.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
I will leave you to imagine the astonishment of the Child of Nature on his way there. At first he thought it was a dream, and sat paralysed, until suddenly he was seized by a fit of anger which redoubled his strength. Grasping two of his guards by the throat, he threw them out of the carriage door and hurled himself after them, pulling along the third, who was trying to hold him back. The effort brought him to the ground, and he was tied up and put back in the carriage.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Look at that!\u8217? he said. \u8216?That\u8217?s what one gets for chasing the English out of Lower Brittany. What would you say, my lovely St Yves, if you saw me in this state?\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
At last they arrived at the quarters which were destined for him. He was borne in silence into the room where he was to be shut up, like a corpse that is carried to the cemetery. The room was already occupied by an old man, a \u8216?hermit\u8217? from the Port Royal called Gordon, who had languished in it for two years.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Hallo there,\u8217? said the chief of the myrmidons. \u8216?Here\u8217?s some company I\u8217?ve brought you.\u8217? Without more ado the huge bolts of the thick door were thrust into their sockets and secured with great bars. The two prisoners were cut off from the whole universe.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{\par\pard\hyphpar }{\page } {\s1 \afs32
