THE CHILD OF NATURE\u8217?S OPINIONS ON PLAYS\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
THE Child of Nature was like one of those hardy trees which begin life in unpromising soil and throw out their roots and branches as soon as they are transplanted into a more favourable locality. Strange as it may seem, it was life in prison which provided this locality.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
Among the books which occupied the leisure of the two captives, there was some poetry, some translations of Greek tragedy, and a few French plays. The love poetry he read filled the soul of our Child of Nature with both pleasure and grief, for it all spoke to him of his dear St Yves. La Fontaine\u8217?s fable of the two pigeons touched him to the very heart, for it was so far beyond his power to return to his dovecot.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
He was delighted with Moli\u232?re, who made him acquainted with the customs of Paris and indeed of the human race.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Which of his comedies is your favourite?\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
{\i
\u8216?Tartuffe}, without a doubt.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?I agree with you,\u8217? said Gordon. \u8216?It was a Tartuffe who plunged me into this dungeon, and perhaps it is the Tartuffes who are responsible for your misfortunes. What do you think of these Greek tragedies?\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Good enough for the Greeks,\u8217? replied the Child of Nature. But when he read our modern plays about Iphigenia, Phaedra, Andromache, and Athalia, he was in ecstasy; he sighed, he wept, and he learnt them by heart without even intending to.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Read Corneille\u8217?s {\i
Rodogune},\u8217? Gordon told him. \u8216?They say that is the great masterpiece of the theatre. The other plays that have given you so much pleasure are not to be compared with it.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
Before he had finished the first page, the young man said to him : \u8216?It isn\u8217?t by the same author.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?How do you know?\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?I can\u8217?t tell yet. But these verses appeal neither to my ear nor to my heart.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?Oh, that\u8217?s only the versification,\u8217? replied Gordon.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
The Child of Nature retorted: \u8216?Why write in verse, then?\u8217? He read the play with great care, and no other motive than to find pleasure in it; then he looked at his friend with dry and puzzled eyes, not knowing what to say. At last, pressed to describe what he had felt, he replied in these terms :\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?I hardly understood the beginning, I was shocked by the middle, I was much moved by the last scene, although it seemed to me rather improbable. I could not feel concerned about any of the characters, and I have not remembered twenty lines, though I can remember them all when I like them.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?But this play is considered to be the best we have.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
\u8216?If that is so,\u8217? replied the Huron, \u8216?it is perhaps like so many people who do not deserve their positions. After all, it is a question of taste; no doubt mine isn\u8217?t formed yet, and I could be mistaken. But, as you know, I am used to saying what I think, or rather what I feel. I suspect that men\u8217?s judgements are often influenced by delusion, by fashion, or by caprice. I spoke straight from Nature, and my idea of Nature may be very imperfect, but it may also be that most people rarely consult Nature at all.\u8217?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar} {	
Then he repeated some lines from Racine\u8217?s {\i
Iphig\u233?nie}, of which his head was full, and though he did not recite well, he put so much truth and earnestness into it that he reduced the old Jansenist to tears. After that, he read {\i
Cinna}; it did not make him weep, but it impressed him.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{\par\pard\hyphpar }{\page } {\s1 \afs32
